Top Nine. 
It was quite a year. Lots of making. Lots of changing. Lots of learning. And lots of fun! It was so so nice to take a break from my phone over the Holidays. To be completely honest, we were BURNT OUT, and in desperate need of a recharge. Instagram is such an amazing tool to connect with all of you: friends and strangers from all over the world who appreciate vintage textiles and sustainable fashion, but when it’s also your livelihood, the stress can really pile up. But here we are again! Rested and ready for what 2023 will bring. There will be a lot of exciting new things that are already in the works that we can’t wait to share with you, and plenty of surprises for you all, as well as us, because when you’re a new and small business you never know exactly what is going to happen or where things will lead. We welcome the challenges and opportunities that are sure the present themselves in the new year! 

#sustainablefashion #quiltclothes #quiltclothing #quiltcoat #quiltcoats #motorcyclejacket #bikerjacket #sustainablebusiness

We’re about halfway through January and I’m still reflecting on this past year and working on settling into the new one. There hasn’t been much “content” lately. I’m feeling a need to work slowly, and one of our bigger projects can’t be shared yet. Sometimes when I feel “stuck” or “stagnant,” it helps me to look back at larger chunks of time and I realize that we are in fact growing, even when each individual day feels the same. 2022 was a big year. We got married! Our dog turned 15! And we accomplished some big things: We had more photo shoots than ever and got to work with old friends and make some new ones. We released the Adeline Biker Jacket, which had been a dream in my head and a work in progress for several years. We solidified our brand and Dale designed a line of merch for us (and you!). We started selling our work on Free People, and we hired an amazingly talented sewist to help with the workload. Looking back is a good reminder that this year will sure to be filled with growth for us again, and I hope it is for you all as well, with whatever it is that you’re passionate about or trying to accomplish. 

#kittybadhands #quiltcoat #quiltclothes #sustainablefashion #sustainablestyle #slowfashiob #ooakclothing

Yesterday I fulfilled a lifelong dream of visiting a master weaver and his family in Oaxaca! Jesús Hernández J. Opened his studio to us and shared his knowledge about his weaving process: from carding and spinning the wool used for the loom, to different ways to use natural dyes, and weaving pictorial images. It was emotional, inspiring, and an honor to learn from him. One of his rugs takes 12 weeks of working 7 hours a day to produce and they are some of the most beautiful works of art I have ever seen. I get chills just thinking about how lucky I was to have this experience and if you have the opportunity to visit his studio: Tejidos Zapoteco, I HIGHLY recommend it. 

#oaxaca #oaxacanrugs #oaxacanrug #oaxacanartist #jesushernandez #jesúshernández #weaving #fiberart #textileart #naturaldye

When your clothing is handmade, buttons can be quite a process. 
Marking, sewing button holes, trimming threads, applying no fray, cutting the button holes, lining up the buttons to the button holes, and finally hand sewing each button. 
When we say our clothing is made with love, we aren’t kidding around!

Welcome! It’s been almost 2 years since we’ve introduced ourselves and there are so many new faces here (it’s kinda wild, thank you!) Kitty Badhands is a small, sustainable clothing brand run by me (Kat) and my husband Dale. I started this business in 2020 as a side hobby: making Quilt Coats, and it has blossomed in the past 3 years more than I could have ever imagined! We have expanded our clothing to a full line of wearables, hired an incredibly talented part-time sewist, have had so many of our gorgeous friends model for us, have our clothing and accessories at Free People, and have learned SO MUCH! One thing that hasn’t changed is our commitment to making clothes that combat fast fashion and are kind to the environment. We source vintage and natural fiber textiles, and we use every part of the fabric: scraps get made into smaller accessories, and what we can’t use gets donated to local artists and makers. We live in Vermont with our (soon to be) 16 year old dog Rosa, and all of our clothing is made right here in VT. It’s has been and continues to be a wild ride and we are learning and growing everyday. Thank you for being here! 

#makersgonnamake #makersmovement #smallbusinessowner #sustainablefashion #sustainableclothing #sewistsofinstagram #ecofashion #vintagetextiles

Our hats are meant to sit over your ears, and they do not have any stretch! That’s why it’s important to read the below instructions. For example: with my ears I’m a 22” (21.5” standard) and I can wear the Petite OR Regular. 

1. Measure around your head, angling from the nape of your neck to around your forehead. 

2. INCLUDE YOUR EARS ⭐️or if you know your standard head measurement already, add half an inch! 

Petite: for 21.5”- 22” heads

Regular: for 22”- 22.75” heads 

Large: 23”-23.25” heads

X-Large: 23.5”-23.75” heads

If you’re in doubt: DM me!
